	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">IvanDSM wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">* Old NESICIDE had a pattern drawer, assembly maker (joining 4 patterns) and nametable drawer. The Graphics Bank designer is messy, unconfortable and very difficult for people who don't know a bit of 6502 asm!<br /></div><br />Yes, due to "popular demand" I've decided to put some energy into the palette/tile designers in NESICIDE 2.  I'm not sure what you mean by "messy".  The Graphics Bank designer is merely a mechanism to organize the binary files (or, once completed, tiles from the tile designer) into an 8K CHR.  You don't need to know 6502 assembly to use the Graphics Bank.  <br /><div class="quotetitle">IvanDSM wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">*The same thing with sprites. It also had a rom designer where you chose your mapper, additional VRAM on/off, SaveRAM, Trainer. Also: Ifound no support for TRAINER banks. To be honest, NESICIDE1 was like making PRG,CHR,draw,code,compile,yay! NESICIDE2 is so... "naked".</div>
<br />TRAINER banks are never or very rarely used.  I'm glad you had a simple experience with NESICIDE 1.  I hope to bring enough of its functionality into NESICIDE 2 so the experience can be replicated there.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


